      "writtenOn": "2017-04-05T13:57:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e I don\u0027t understand this.\n\u003e \n\u003e It seems you are trying to find all possible groupings of failures, since whether or not maybeMerge merges depends on the order of previous merges. However, in order to do that, you would need to iterate over all possible permutations of failures, since B.maybeMerge(A).maybeMerge(C) could give different results from B.maybeMerge(C).maybeMerge(A).\n\u003e \n\nYuck. Changed to find all permutations of failures and added a test which fails with the current n^2 algorithm.  Obviously this needs to improve before it\u0027s used in production.\n\n\u003e Also, it seems like rather than generating all possible groupings, we really want to partition failures into groups, i.e. no two groups should contain the same failure. However, the deduplication below doesn\u0027t achieve that -- it only deduplicates identical groups.\n\nI disagree.  We don\u0027t want to limit a failure to a single group unless we\u0027re 100% sure that, logically, the failure MUST belong in that group and only that group.  IMO making the decision of which group is most likely is the job of a future pipeline stage, probably one that incorporates user feedback.  Per our live discussion, this is all far from done.",
